## Core Components

Core components are the basic building blocks of your interface. They show up everywhere in your product, like buttons, inputs, and toggles. Reusing them helps reduce design and tech debt, keeps things consistent, and speeds up development.

### Accordion (Collapse)

- [ ] **Open vs Closed** - Two main states. If there's an icon (like an arrow), it should clearly show which state it's in. (WCAG: 1.3.1, 1.3.2, 1.4.13)
- [ ] **Composition** - The content area should be flexible. It should work with text, images, or even other components inside. (WCAG: 1.3.1, 1.3.2)
- [ ] **Toggle Transition** - Use a smooth, simple animation when opening or closing. (WCAG: 2.2.1, 2.2.3, 2.3, 2.3.1, 2.3.2, 2.3.3)
- [ ] **Content & Trigger Relation** - Make sure assistive tech can link the content to the trigger. (WCAG: 1.3.5, 1.3.6, 2.1.1–2.1.3, 2.4.3, 2.4.11–2.4.13, 2.5.3, 2.5.5, 2.5.8, 4.1.1)

### Alert

- [ ] **Color** - Use different background colors to show the type of alert. Make sure the text inside has enough contrast. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.6, 1.4.11)
- [ ] **Title Support** - Including a title helps users quickly get the point, especially if the alert has a longer message. (WCAG: 2.4.6, 3.1.2, 3.1.4–3.1.6, 4.1.3)
- [ ] **Icon Support** - Icons help explain what the alert is about and are useful for people who can't rely on color alone. (WCAG: 1.1.1, 1.3.5, 1.4.5)
- [ ] **Actions** - If there's something the user needs to do, include a clear action button or link. (WCAG: 1.3.6, 2.4.3, 2.4.4, 3.1.2)
- [ ] **Responsiveness** - Make sure alerts adjust to screen size. On smaller screens, they should go full-width. (WCAG: 1.4.4, 1.4.10)
- [ ] **Accessibility Role** - Use the correct accessibility role so screen readers know to announce the alert properly. (WCAG: 1.3.6, 2.1.1–2.1.4, 2.4.3, 2.4.11–2.4.13, 2.5.3, 4.1.1)

### Avatar

- [ ] **Image** - Avatars should crop images into the right shape and handle whatever image size gets thrown at them. (WCAG: 1.1.1, 1.4.11)
- [ ] **Image Fallback** - If the image doesn't load, show an icon or initials instead. (WCAG: 1.1.1, 1.4.11)
- [ ] **Size** - Include small, medium, and large options at minimum. (WCAG: 2.5.5, 2.5.8)
- [ ] **Color** - When there's no image, use a background color that meets contrast guidelines. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.6, 1.4.11)
- [ ] **Avatar Groups** - Stack a few avatars together to show a group of users.
- [ ] **Accessibility Label** - If there's no visible name, make sure screen readers can describe what or who the avatar represents. (WCAG: 1.3.6, 2.1.1–2.1.3, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.11–2.4.13, 2.5.3, 4.1.1)

### Badge (Chip & Tag)

- [ ] **Color** - Use different colors to show different meanings. Make sure text or icon on top has enough contrast. Not the sole meaning of status for colorblind users. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.6, 1.4.11)
- [ ] **Variants** - Some can be bold and bright, others more subtle with soft backgrounds. (WCAG: 1.4.1)
- [ ] **Size** - A few size options so badges work in different spots. (WCAG: 2.5.5, 2.5.8)
- [ ] **Icon Support** - Add icons next to the text to help show meaning fast. (WCAG: 1.1.1, 1.3.5, 1.4.5)
- [ ] **Dismissable** - If showing a selected filter, make it possible to remove it with a close button. (WCAG: 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.4, 2.4.7, 2.4.11–2.4.13, 2.5.3, 2.5.5, 2.5.8, 3.2.1)
- [ ] **Empty State** - Some badges don't need text, like a small dot for status. Adjust the style so they still look right.
- [ ] **Positioning** - For notification indicators, badges should be easy to place in the corner of an icon or avatar. (WCAG: 1.1.1, 1.3.6, 1.4.9)

### Button

- [ ] **Color** - Use different colors for different button roles. Always meet WCAG AA contrast standards. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.6, 1.4.11)
- [ ] **Variants** - Primary buttons should stand out, secondary or subtle buttons can blend in more. (WCAG: 1.4.1)
- [ ] **Size** - Have a few sizes ready. Smaller for tight spaces, larger for touch-heavy areas. (WCAG: 2.5.5, 2.5.8)
- [ ] **Icon Support** - Can include icons alongside text or stand alone as icon-only. Icon-only needs accessibility label. (WCAG: 1.1.1, 1.3.5, 1.4.5)
- [ ] **Hover State** - Show a clear visual change on hover. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3)
- [ ] **Focus State** - Show a visible focus ring or style for keyboard/assistive tech users. (WCAG: 1.4.3, 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.11–2.4.13, 3.2.1)
- [ ] **Active State** - Show feedback when clicked or toggled. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3)
- [ ] **Loading State** - Show a loading indicator. Button shouldn't change size when loading. (WCAG: 2.5.2)
- [ ] **Disabled State** - Should look inactive and not respond to clicks or taps. (WCAG: 2.5.2)
- [ ] **Accessibility Role** - Announced correctly by screen readers. Use the right role based on what it does. (WCAG: 2.4.4, 2.4.6, 2.5.3, 4.2.1)

### Breadcrumb

- [ ] **Icon Support** - Use icons consistently next to breadcrumb items. (WCAG: 1.1.1, 1.3.5, 1.4.5)
- [ ] **Disabled State** - Allow individual items to be disabled when needed. (WCAG: 2.5.2)
- [ ] **Collapsed State** - If there isn't enough room, collapse the middle items so the first and last few stay visible.
- [ ] **Separator** - Use a separator that fits your design—but keep it consistent.

### Calendar (Date & Time Pickers)

- [ ] **Display Modes** - Support different layouts (single month, multi-month, vertical stack).
- [ ] **Selected State** - Users should be able to pick one date or a range. Highlight clearly.
- [ ] **Month Selection** - Make it easy to switch between months.
- [ ] **Day Names** - Show short weekday labels above the date numbers.
- [ ] **Internationalization** - Support different regions, languages, local date formats, and weekday order.
- [ ] **Keyboard Navigation** - All dates keyboard focusable. Arrow keys to move, screen readers navigate smoothly. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.11–2.4.13, 3.2.1)
- [ ] **State Announcement** - Assistive tech should announce selected or focused dates clearly. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.11–2.4.13, 3.2.1, 4.1.1, 4.1.2)

### Card

- [ ] **Composition** - Flexible inside. Works with text, images, buttons, or other components. Consider reading order for assistive devices. (WCAG: 1.3.1, 1.3.2)
- [ ] **Media** - Cards often include images or videos at the top or side.
- [ ] **Actions** - Buttons or links, usually at the bottom. Sometimes the whole card can be clickable. (WCAG: 1.3.6, 2.4.3, 2.4.4, 3.1.2)
- [ ] **Responsiveness** - On smaller screens, cards should stretch to full width. (WCAG: 1.4.4, 1.4.10)
- [ ] **Groups** - Stack multiple cards in a list or grid for related items.

### Carousel (Slider)

- [ ] **Navigation** - Users can move through using mouse controls, not just swipe or drag.
- [ ] **Composition** - Each carousel item should hold different kinds of content. (WCAG: 1.3.1, 1.3.2)
- [ ] **Size** - On smaller screens, show part of the next item to hint that more content is scrollable. (WCAG: 2.5.5, 2.5.8)
- [ ] **Touch** - Scrollable with touch gestures on mobile.
- [ ] **Responsiveness** - Adjust layout based on screen size. (WCAG: 1.4.4, 1.4.10)
- [ ] **Keyboards** - Users should be able to move through with keyboard and screen readers.

### Checkbox

- [ ] **Label** - Every checkbox should have a label. Clicking the label toggles the checkbox. (WCAG: 2.4.6, 3.3.2)
- [ ] **Checked State** - Show clearly when selected.
- [ ] **Error State** - Show error message and change field color. Include both visual and text feedback. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 3.3.1, 3.3.3, 3.3.4)
- [ ] **Disabled State** - Non-interactive. Doesn't send data when submitted. (WCAG: 2.5.2)
- [ ] **Intermediate State** - Shows when only some options in a group are selected (dash or shaded box).
- [ ] **Grouping** - Group multiple checkboxes for related options. (WCAG: 1.3.1, 1.3.2)
- [ ] **Accessibility** - Works with keyboard. Include hover, focus, and active states. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.11–2.4.13, 3.2.1)

### Divider

- [ ] **Direction** - Works in both horizontal and vertical layouts.
- [ ] **Accessibility Role** - If marking a meaningful break in content, assistive tech can announce its role.

### Dropdown

- [ ] **Composition** - Flexible enough to hold icons, text, or other components. Consider reading and focus order. (WCAG: 1.3.1, 1.3.2)
- [ ] **Hover & Focus State** - Opens on hover and also works for keyboard users on focus. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.11–2.4.13, 3.2.1)
- [ ] **Dynamic Positioning** - Opens in a direction that keeps it visible. Never gets cut off.
- [ ] **Responsiveness** - Adjusts to fit smaller screens. (WCAG: 1.4.4, 1.4.10)
- [ ] **Focus Trapping** - Focus moves inside when open. Returns to trigger on close.
- [ ] **Keyboard Navigation** - Arrow keys to move through items, Escape to close, screen readers announce contents.

### Icon

- [ ] **Color** - Use color tokens. Should also inherit color from parent element. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.6, 1.4.11)
- [ ] **Size** - A few standard sizes that line up with your typography scale. (WCAG: 2.5.5, 2.5.8)
- [ ] **Interactivity** - If clickable, wrap in a proper interactive element like a button or link.

### Image

- [ ] **Image Fallback** - If image doesn't load, show a background color, icon, or placeholder.
- [ ] **Alt Text** - Always include alt text if the image has meaning. Skip if purely decorative.
- [ ] **Size** - Support flexible width, height, and aspect ratio. (WCAG: 2.5.5, 2.5.8)
- [ ] **Screen Density Support** - Support different image sizes for different screen resolutions.

### Link

- [ ] **Icon Support** - Icons can give extra context. Don't use icons by themselves—always include text label. (WCAG: 1.1.1, 1.3.5, 1.4.5)
- [ ] **Color** - Follow color tokens. Check contrast meets WCAG AA against backgrounds and adjacent text. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.6, 1.4.11)
- [ ] **Disabled State** - Should look inactive and not respond to clicks. (WCAG: 2.5.2)
- [ ] **Font Inheritance** - Links in text should match the typography around them.
- [ ] **Multiline Display** - Links inside paragraphs should wrap across lines without breaking layout.
- [ ] **Accessibility** - Announced correctly by screen readers. Use the right role (link or button). Underlines encouraged.

### List

- [ ] **Order** - Use bullets, numbers, or custom markers depending on content.
- [ ] **Composition** - Each list item should support text, icons, or other components. (WCAG: 1.3.1, 1.3.2)
- [ ] **Accessibility** - Assistive tech can recognize the list, its role, and how many items it includes.

### Loading

- [ ] **Color** - Match the color scheme of the area they're in. Use color tokens. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.6, 1.4.11)
- [ ] **Size** - Different sizes depending on where the loader appears. (WCAG: 2.5.5, 2.5.8)
- [ ] **Duration** - Keep visible until it finishes or fails. If timing is known, use a progress bar.
- [ ] **Motion** - Respect reduced motion settings. Slow down or simplify animation.
- [ ] **Accessibility Label** - Add a label so screen readers can announce what's being loaded. (WCAG: 1.3.6, 2.5.3)

### Modal (Dialog)

- [ ] **Composition** - Flexible enough to hold text, forms, media, or other components. (WCAG: 1.3.1, 1.3.2)
- [ ] **Actions** - Put actions in a clear area—usually at the bottom. (WCAG: 1.3.6, 2.4.3, 2.4.4, 3.1.2)
- [ ] **Close** - There should always be a clear way to close the modal.
- [ ] **Positioning** - Usually centered on screen, but can slide in from sides.
- [ ] **Size** - Support different sizes based on the content. (WCAG: 2.5.5, 2.5.8)
- [ ] **Focus Trapping** - Move focus to first focusable element inside. Keep trapped until closed. Return focus to trigger on close.
- [ ] **Keyboard Navigation** - Tab and Shift+Tab through elements. Esc should close.
- [ ] **Title & Subtitle Labeling** - Screen readers can announce title and subtitle. Add accessible label if not visible. (WCAG: 2.4.4, 2.4.6, 2.5.3, 4.2.1)

### Pagination

- [ ] **Selected State** - Clearly show which page is selected. Selected page shouldn't be clickable. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.11–2.4.13, 3.2.1)
- [ ] **Display Ranges** - Show a few pages around the current one, not every page number.
- [ ] **Items per Page** - Give users control over how many items they see per page.
- [ ] **Intermediate or Truncated Pages** - If total pages unknown, use next/previous controls only.
- [ ] **Full Page Label Announcements** - Screen readers announce "Page 3 of 10" instead of just "3."
- [ ] **State Announcements** - Assistive technologies announce focus/selection changes clearly.

### Progress

- [ ] **Label** - Show a clear label that tells users what the progress bar is tracking. (WCAG: 2.4.6, 3.3.2)
- [ ] **Size** - A few size options for different layouts. (WCAG: 2.5.5, 2.5.8)
- [ ] **Duration** - If timing is known, show progress filling up. If not, keep showing until task finishes or fails.
- [ ] **Accessibility Label** - Add an accessibility label if no visible label on screen. (WCAG: 2.5.3)

### Radio

- [ ] **Label** - Every radio button should have a label. Clicking the label selects it. (WCAG: 2.4.6, 3.3.2)
- [ ] **Checked State** - Clearly show which option is selected. (WCAG: 1.4.1)
- [ ] **Error State** - Show error message and change field's visual style. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 3.3.1, 3.3.3, 3.3.4)
- [ ] **Grouping** - Always used in a group. Ensures only one can be picked. (WCAG: 1.3.1, 1.3.2)
- [ ] **Accessibility** - Keyboard selectable. Include hover, focus, active, and disabled states. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.11–2.4.13, 2.5.2, 3.2.1)

### Select

- [ ] **Label** - Every select field should have a text label. Clicking the label opens the dropdown. (WCAG: 2.4.6, 3.3.2)
- [ ] **Error State** - Show an error message and a visual cue like an icon or color change. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 3.3.1, 3.3.3, 3.3.4)
- [ ] **Disabled State** - Non-interactive. Won't send data when submitted. (WCAG: 2.5.2)
- [ ] **Placeholder** - Show a placeholder if nothing is selected yet.
- [ ] **Helper Text** - Add extra text under the field to explain what to choose. (WCAG: 3.3.2)
- [ ] **Icon Support** - Include an icon before selected text for context. (WCAG: 1.1.1, 1.3.5, 1.4.5)
- [ ] **Prefix & Suffix** - Add custom visuals or text like flags, currency symbols.
- [ ] **Accessibility** - Provide an accessibility label if label isn't visible. Cover hover, focus, and active states. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3)

### Skeleton

- [ ] **Size** - Match the size of the real content they're standing in for. (WCAG: 2.5.5, 2.5.8)
- [ ] **Shape** - Use shapes that match real components (circles for avatars, rectangles for text).
- [ ] **Composition** - Group simple skeletons to represent complex layouts. (WCAG: 1.3.1, 1.3.2)
- [ ] **Accessibility** - If reduced motion turned on, slow down or remove animation. (WCAG: 2.3.1, 2.3.2, 2.3.3)

### Switch (Toggle)

- [ ] **Label** - Every switch should have a label. Clicking label toggles. (WCAG: 2.4.6, 3.3.2)
- [ ] **Checked State** - When on, show it clearly. Communicate state with more than just color.
- [ ] **Disabled State** - Shouldn't respond to clicks, taps, or key presses. (WCAG: 2.5.2)
- [ ] **Keyboard** - Users should be able to toggle using keyboard.
- [ ] **Accessibility** - Provide an accessible name if no visible label.

### Tabs (Segmented)

- [ ] **Composition** - Content under each tab supports text, images, forms, or other components. (WCAG: 1.3.1, 1.3.2)
- [ ] **Variants** - Tabs can look different depending on context (pill-style, underlined, etc.).
- [ ] **Selected State** - One tab always selected by default, visually highlighted.
- [ ] **Disabled State** - Specific tabs can be disabled. Shouldn't respond to clicks or keyboard. (WCAG: 2.5.2)
- [ ] **Icon Support** - Add icons next to tab labels if it helps explain content. (WCAG: 1.1.1, 1.3.5, 1.4.5)
- [ ] **Equal Width** - When spanning full width, stretch each tab to take equal space.
- [ ] **Accessibility** - Full keyboard navigation. Arrow keys to move, Home/End to jump to first/last.

### Text Area

- [ ] **Label** - Every text area should have a label. Clicking label moves focus to field. (WCAG: 2.4.6, 3.3.2)
- [ ] **Error State** - Show error message and visual style change. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 3.3.1, 3.3.3, 3.3.4)
- [ ] **Disabled State** - Looks inactive and won't send data when submitted. (WCAG: 2.5.2)
- [ ] **Placeholder** - Used for hints only, not as replacement for labels.
- [ ] **Helper Text** - Extra info under the field if users need guidance. (WCAG: 3.3.2)
- [ ] **Size** - Different sizes for different layouts. (WCAG: 2.5.5, 2.5.8)
- [ ] **Accessibility** - Include accessibility label if no label on screen.

### Text Field

- [ ] **Label** - Every text field should have a label. Clicking label moves focus to field. (WCAG: 2.4.6, 3.3.2)
- [ ] **Error State** - Show error message and change visual style. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 3.3.1, 3.3.3, 3.3.4)
- [ ] **Disabled State** - Looks inactive and won't send value when submitted. (WCAG: 2.5.2)
- [ ] **Placeholder** - For examples or short hints, not label replacement.
- [ ] **Helper Text** - Show extra info below the field when users need guidance. (WCAG: 3.3.2)
- [ ] **Icon Support** - Place an icon inside the field for context (e.g., search icon). (WCAG: 1.1.1, 1.3.5, 1.4.5)
- [ ] **Prefix & Suffix** - For added context like dollar sign for prices.
- [ ] **Size** - Multiple size options for different contexts. (WCAG: 2.5.5, 2.5.8)
- [ ] **Accessibility** - Provide accessibility label if no visible label.

### Toast (Message)

- [ ] **Composition** - Flexible enough to include text, icons, buttons, or other components. (WCAG: 1.3.1, 1.3.2)
- [ ] **Color** - Add an icon at the start to help users quickly understand the purpose—especially helpful for colorblind users. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.6, 1.4.11)
- [ ] **Icon Support** - Include a clear button to dismiss if they don't close automatically. (WCAG: 1.1.1, 1.3.5, 1.4.5)
- [ ] **Timeout** - Disappear after a short delay. Make sure users have enough time to read them. (WCAG: 2.2.1–2.2.6)
- [ ] **Stacking** - When multiple toasts are triggered, stack them neatly so they don't overlap.
- [ ] **Actions** - If the toast has an action (Undo, Retry), make it contextual and clear. (WCAG: 1.3.6, 2.4.3, 2.4.4, 3.1.2)
- [ ] **Focus** - If toast includes actions, they should be keyboard-focusable. While focused, toast shouldn't auto-dismiss. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.11–2.4.13, 3.2.1)
- [ ] **Motion** - If reduced motion enabled, simplify or turn off animations. (WCAG: 2.2.1–2.2.3, 2.3.1, 2.3.2, 2.3.3)

### Tooltip

- [ ] **Position** - Show quick info when user hovers over or focuses on an element. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3)
- [ ] **Timeout** - Add a short delay before showing to avoid them popping up during mouse movement. (WCAG: 2.2.1–2.2.6)
- [ ] **Keyboard** - Appear on keyboard focus too, not just hover. (WCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.11–2.4.13, 3.2.1)

